               <interp inst="t18441125-197" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18441125"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18441125-197" type="date" value="18441125"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18441125-197-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-197-18441125 t18441125-197-offence-1 t18441125-197-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>197. <persName id="def1-197-18441125" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-197-18441125" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-197-18441125" type="age" value="17"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-197-18441125" type="surname" value="GARROOD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-197-18441125" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">EDWARD GARROOD</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18441125-197-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18441125-197-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18441125-197-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="fraud"></interp> for obtaining money by false pretences.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18441125-name-1155" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18441125-name-1155" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18441125-name-1155" type="surname" value="CHAPMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18441125-name-1155" type="given" value="ANTHONY"></interp>ANTHONY CHAPMAN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable V</hi> 100.) I reside at Tooting, in Surrey. On Sunday, the 3rd of Nov., about twelve or one o'clock, the prisoner brought a parcel to my house—he had been conductor to an om<lb></lb>nibus—on the paper parcel he brought there was "2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>." marked, and he demanded 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for the carriage—it had come from the New Inn, Old Bailey—I said, "3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.?"—he said, "Yes, here is the bill, 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. paid out, and 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. carriage"—my sister-in-law paid him the 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in my presence—unless I had believed that "2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>." had been paid out, and 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. was due for carriage, I should not have paid it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you say you thought it was too much? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I did—I thought the whole of it was too much—I believe the prisoner was in the service of Mr. Holden, the omnibus pro<lb></lb>prietor—after he was gone, it struck me there had been an alteration in the bill, from 1 to 2—the prisoner was not taken for ten days afterwards—he was not in the town.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18441125-name-1156" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18441125-name-1156" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18441125-name-1156" type="surname" value="MILLER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18441125-name-1156" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES MILLER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the service of the Merton carrier. On Sun<lb></lb>day, the 3rd of Nov., in the morning, my master gave me a parcel, directed to Mr. Chapman—I carried it to Tooting—the prisoner came up to me, and asked where I was going—I said to Mr. Chapman's, and I asked him if he could tell me where it was—he said he would go with me and take it—I said I should be very glad if he could assist me—the money he ought to have received on that parcel was 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—there was 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. marked on the bill, and 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. was the carriage from London—I gave him the parcel to take—we got to Mr. Chapman's, and he took it in—I gave him the bill—this is it—it has been altered from 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. to 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> When you first saw him, did you not ask where Mr. Chapman lived? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He asked me where I was going, and then I asked him where Mr. Chapman lived—it was on Tooting-common I gave him the parcel to deliver—he went to one Mr. Chapman, which was not right—he brought me the parcel out, and still kept possession of the bill—we went on as far as the church, and then he took the parcel, and said he knew where it was—he was gone four or five minutes, and then came back, and brought me half-a-crown—James Pincott and Thomas Tappin were with me on the common—I was in Mr. Pincott's service, but have left, to go to a public-house—I gave Mr. Pincott a week's notice—he kept me till I got a place—I have never been at Brixton or Guildford, nor in any gaol at all—I do not mean to swear that I never told anybody so, but I have never been there—I might have said it to some of the boys on</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184411250233"></xptr>
               <p>Tooting-common, but it was not so—I do not know that I have said so—I might.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18441125-name-1157" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18441125-name-1157" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18441125-name-1157" type="surname" value="REED"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18441125-name-1157" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH REED</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable V</hi> 243.) I took the prisoner on Tooting common—he laid down on his back, and asked me what I wanted with him—I told him he knew—he said, "I know nothing but the parcel I took to Chapman"—I said, "That was all wrong"—he said, "I gave Miller the money."</p>
               <p>(Edmund Craven, a wheelwright, and Ellen Simpson, of Tooting, gave the prisoner a good character.)</p>
               <p>
